Explainer &lt;a rel="nofollow" href="https://github.com/w3c/csswg-drafts/blob/main/css-values-5/tree-counting-explainer.md"&gt;https://github.com/w3c/csswg-drafts/blob/main/css-values-5/tree-counting-explainer.md&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;pre&gt;
Specification&lt;a rel="nofollow" href="https://drafts.csswg.org/css-values-5/#tree-counting"&gt;https://drafts.csswg.org/css-values-5/#tree-counting&lt;/a&gt;
Design docs &lt;a rel="nofollow" href="https://github.com/w3c/csswg-drafts/blob/main/css-values-5/tree-counting-explainer.md"&gt;https://github.com/w3c/csswg-drafts/blob/main/css-values-5/tree-counting-explainer.md&lt;/a&gt;
Summary
sibling-index() and sibling-count() can be used as integers in CSS property values to style elements based on their position among its siblings, or the total number of siblings respectively. These functions can be used directly as integer values, but more interestingly inside calc() expressions. Example: li { margin-left: calc(10px * sibling-index()); }
Blink componentBlink&gt;CSS &lt;&lt;a rel="nofollow" href="https://issues.chromium.org/issues?q=customfield1222907:%22Blink%3ECSS%22"&gt;https://issues.chromium.org/issues?q=customfield1222907:%22Blink%3ECSS%22&lt;/a&gt;&gt;
